conversations.original_question: Patient: Linda Harris, Age: 54, SSN: 159-75-3486, Address: 147 Birch Road. Question: I woke up this morning feeling the whole room is spinning when i was sitting down. I went to the bathroom walking unsteadily, as i tried to focus i feel nauseous. I try to vomit but it wont come out.. After taking panadol and sleep for few hours, i still feel the same.. By the way, if i lay down or sit down, my head do not spin, only when i want to move around then i feel the whole world is spinning.. And it is normal stomach discomfort at the same time? Earlier after i relieved myself, the spinning lessen so i am not sure whether its connected or coincidences.. Thank you doc!

messages.message:
It sounds like you're experiencing symptoms of vertigo, which is a sensation that the room is spinning. This can be accompanied by nausea and unsteadiness. Vertigo can have various causes, such as inner ear issues, dehydration, or other medical conditions. It's good to note that the symptoms lessen when you're still, which is common with certain types of vertigo.

For now, try to stay hydrated and avoid sudden movements that might trigger the spinning sensation. It's important to consult with a healthcare professional to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment. They may suggest specific exercises or medications to help manage the symptoms. If your symptoms persist or worsen, seek medical attention promptly.

conversations.original_question: Age: 75, Phone: 555-789-0123. Question: Their baby has been pooing 5-6 times a day for a week. In the last few days it has increased to 7 and they are very watery with green stringy bits in them. He does not seem unwell i.e no temperature and still eating. He now has a very bad nappy rash from the pooing ...help!

messages.message:

The green stringy bits might be related to bile or undigested food. Since your baby doesn't have a fever and is still eating, that's a positive sign, but the persistent diarrhea and nappy rash should be addressed.

For the nappy rash, you can try:
- Changing diapers more frequently to keep the area dry.
- Using a barrier cream or ointment to protect the skin.
- Allowing some diaper-free time to let the skin breathe.

If the diarrhea continues or worsens, or if your baby shows any signs of dehydration (such as dry mouth, fewer wet diapers, or lethargy), it's important to consult a pediatrician for further evaluation and guidance. conversations.original_question: Patient: Sarah Johnson, Address: 321 Elm Drive. Question: Hello, Their husband is taking Oxycodone due to a broken leg/surgery. He has been taking this pain medication for one month. We are trying to conceive our second baby. Will this medication afect the fetus? Or the health of the baby? Or can it bring birth defects? Thank you.

messages.message:
It's important to consider the potential effects of medications like Oxycodone when trying to conceive. Oxycodone is an opioid, and while there is limited data on its direct impact on fertility, it is known that opioids can affect hormone levels, which might influence fertility in some individuals.

Regarding pregnancy, opioids can cross the placenta and may affect the developing fetus. Prolonged use during pregnancy can lead to neonatal opioid withdrawal syndrome (NOWS) or other complications. It's crucial to discuss any concerns about medication use and family planning with a healthcare provider. They can provide personalized advice and consider alternative pain management options if necessary. Always consult with a healthcare professional before making any changes to medication or treatment plans.
